{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ae2df626-bd82-4cce-9dca-17e221e5b7ef","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK went up → workloads need to go up too → `dotnet workload update`.\n\nIf issues persist after updating, you can also try:\n```bash\ndotnet workload update --from-previous-sdk\n```\nThis carries forward workloads that were installed for your previous SDK version.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ca49ea22-7586-4ed8-acd3-bbce2331d761","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to look at any files or run any commands.","outputTokens":259,"requestId":"3C30:30490E:D03D31:103E426:6A0128B7"},"id":"3c9efd65-7d5f-4a7e-9772-9cdc1a3cdd1f","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:54:22.625Z","parentId":"54fb6b9a-95d9-4dec-844e-f542cd1b4dcc"}
